(8,	'Anti-Stock Theft Branch Meet with Butchery owners',	'<p>\r\n	Butchery owners in Gaborone and the periphery have been urged to follow laws and regulations governing the sale and slaughtering of livestock.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The urge was made by the Divisional Commander South Central, Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police Mr Matthews Letsholo at a workshop held at Tsholofelo Hall&nbsp;<span data-term=\\\"goog_2030308306\\\" tabindex=\\\"0\\\">on Tuesday</span>&nbsp;(<span data-term=\\\"goog_2030308307\\\" tabindex=\\\"0\\\">12/09/17</span>).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	He said stock theft is a concern in the country and therefore there is a need for other stakeholders in the livestock industry to help the police in reducing the stealing of livestock.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	He also pleaded with butchery owners to follow the laws governing the sale of livestock and produce to avoid buying stolen stock.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	For his part the Director of Anti Stock Theft Branch Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police Mr Goboletswe Dimeku said for effective crime prevention butchery owners need to cluster themselves in their business locations.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	He urged other stakeholders involved in the sale and slaughtering of livestock to improve effectively collaborate to avoid night delivery of stock because it is an offence.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The purpose of the workshop was to sensitize butchery owners and other stakeholders about the Stock Theft Act. It was attended by police officers, Gaborone City council, veterinary, and butchery owners.</p>\r\n',	NULL,	'news',	NULL,	'2017-09-12',	'news_8.jpg',	'yes',	'no',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'12:46:24',	0,	NULL,	NULL,	NULL),
(9,	'Anti-Stock Theft Pitso, Letlhakane',	'<p>\r\n	Farmers in Letlhakane and surrounding areas have been called upon to look after their cattle to reduce cases of stock theft.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The call was made by the Director of Anti-Stock Theft Branch, Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police Mr Goboletswe Dimeku at an Anti-Stock Theft Pitso in Mmea lands in the Boteti Sub District&nbsp;<span data-term=\\\"goog_2030308308\\\" tabindex=\\\"0\\\">on Thursday</span>&nbsp;(14/09/17).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	He said some farmers have left the care and management of their stock with their herdsmen and spend extended periods of time without taking stock of their livestock.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Mr Dimeku said livestock contribute significantly to the economy of Botswana therefore, it is important for farmers to protect their livestock from being stolen for the benefit of the country.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	He urged farmers and other stakeholders to come up with firm strategies geared towards reduction of stock theft and not only rely on the police.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Mr Dimeku urged farmers to brand, and earmark their stock as criminals take advantage to steal stock that is unbranded, not earmarked, and left roaming without any one looking after it.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	He also expressed concern about complainants who withdraw cases that are before courts or opt for settlement out of court saying offenders escape the good intention of the law. Mr Dimeku also edged farmers in the Boteti District to form farmers committees and not delegate herdsmen.</p>\r\n',	NULL,	'news',	NULL,	'2017-09-14',	'news_9.jpg',	'yes',	'no',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'12:45:29',	0,	NULL,	NULL,	NULL),
