(124,	'Home vision mission',	'<div class=\\\"commissioner\\\">\r\n	<div class=\\\"thumb\\\">\r\n		<img alt=\\\"Commissioner of Police\\\" src=\\\"/images/commissioner.jpg\\\" /></div>\r\n	<div class=\\\"thumbtxt\\\">\r\n		<p>\r\n			Commissioner of Police</p>\r\n		<p class=\\\"name\\\">\r\n			Mr Keabetswe Makgophe</p>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!--/commissioner-->\r\n<div class=\\\"visiontxt\\\">\r\n	<h3>\r\n		Vision</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		To be a law enforcement agency of Repute.</p>\r\n	<div class=\\\"smlgap\\\">\r\n		&nbsp;</div>\r\n	<h3>\r\n		Mission</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		To provide a professional policing service in partnership with the community.</p>\r\n	<div class=\\\"smlgap\\\">\r\n		&nbsp;</div>\r\n	<h3>\r\n		Values</h3>\r\n	<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n		<li>\r\n			Botho</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Excellence</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Integrity</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			Team Work</li>\r\n		<li>\r\n			another</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	<div class=\\\"smlgap\\\">\r\n		&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!--/visiontxt-->',	'Home vision mission',	'mcms',	'2',	'2017-11-30',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=124',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:34:03',	2,	NULL,	'',	''),
(125,	'History of BPS ',	' <div class=\"thumblt\"><img src=\"/possbpser/illus-157.jpg\" alt=\"illus 157 hoisting the flag at the police training depot at gaberones nov 1960\"></div>\r\n<p>\r\n	The history of policing in this country dates back to the colonial era with the establishment of the Bechuanaland Mounted Police in 1885 headed by Lieutenant Colonel Frederick Carrington, with a strength of 500 men. A year later the name changed to Bechuanaland Border Police and then to Bechuanaland Protectorate Police in 1902. In 1966 Bechuanaland Protectorate Police became Botswana Police Force after the country attained independence from the British rule.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Some natives of the Protectorate perceived the police institution as foreign, particularly that most police officers were migrants from Basutoland (current Lesotho) and Southern Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe). Qualifications for enlisting was more inclined to physique and height as opposed to academic qualifications, thus portraying police officers as confrontational, scary and always all out to pounce on the unsuspecting public.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	These perceptions, apparently contributed to creating a drift between the police and the public they were supposed to serve. It should however, be noted that even where there is mutual understanding between the police and the public, some people still view each other with suspicion. This retrogressive behaviour has inadvertently contributed to the various causes of the ascension of crime and benefited the criminal fraternity.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This state of affairs remained so for years until a deliberate move was taken to localise policing by enlisting Batswana in the Police Force. The legacy from the past was carried on albeit an improved state owing to the fact that the locals were only brought in as messengers and getting a rank beyond trooper was an envy to the handful of Batswana cadres. With the dawn of independence came some transformation that entailed the fast tracking of a localisation programme. However, the police leadership remained in the hands of the whites until 1971 when Mr Simon Hirschfeld was appointed the first Motswana Police Commissioner. He retired in 1995 after serving as Police Commissioner for 24 consecutive years.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Three other Batswana have since served as Commissioners, and they are Messrs Norman Seduma Moleboge (1995 -2004), and Edwin Jenamiso Batshu (2004 - 2007). The incumbent Thebeyame Edward Tsimako succeeded the former in June 2007.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In 1971 the first batch of eight (8) women, comprising Ms Cynthia Keakantswe, Sylvia Muzila, Ednah Gilika, Kgomotso Mosimanyana, Didimalang Koronomio, Vivian Mhaladi, Audry Busang and Annah Matshego was recruited into the Police. Since then, women numbers have been increasing with each police recruitment.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The Commissioner of Police is appointed by the President of the Republic of Botswana as the Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces in terms of Section 112 (2) (e) of the Constitution of Botswana. He is accountable to the Minister of Defence, Justice and Security and currently he is deputised by two Deputy Commissioners responsible for Operations and the other for Support Services. The Police Service is also made up of 12 branches; General Duties, Special Support Group, Criminal Investigations Department, Departmental Management Services, Transport and Telecommunications, Botswana Police College, Traffic, Forensic Science Services, Air Support, Finance, Planning and Development, Crime Intelligence Branch, and Performance Management Systems.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	In addition to branches there are three Divisions; North, South Central and South, led by Divisional Commanders. Within Divisions are 15 Districts, which are commanded by Officer Commanders, and 79 Police Stations led by Station Commanders. The strength of 500 men in 1885 has increased to over 10 000 with the merger of the Botswana Local Police Force and the Botswana Police Service in 2009. Apart from the regular police officers, there are Special Constables, who were introduced in 2004 to enhance police visibility. Late in 2009, BPS introduced Police Volunteers to further augment police patrols.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n',	'History of BPS ',	'mcms',	'3',	'2017-11-30',	NULL,	'',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=125',	NULL,	NULL,	'15:21:32',	5,	NULL,	'',	''),
