(190,	'Operations HQ',	'<p>The BPS Operations Headquarters is tasked with giving strategic  direction to all the operational Branches/units of the BPS. It also deals with  the national threats and crime trends. It is lead by Senior Assistant  Commissioner of Police, Operations (SACP (O)), reporting directly to Deputy  Commissioner of Police for strategic direction.&nbsp; There are&nbsp;&nbsp;  three units which are reporting directly to (SACP (O)) namely:</p>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Crime Reports &amp;  Statistics, Complaints &amp; Commendations and &nbsp;Firearms Registry </li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;Communications </li>\r\n    <li>Stock Theft.&nbsp; </li>\r\n  </ul><br/>\r\n\r\n<h3>Crime Reports & Statistics, Complaints & Commendation, Firearms Registry And Administration Unit</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This unit has the following responsibilities:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>To provide a focused  study of the crime situation in the country and identify emerging crime trends  and challenges. </li>\r\n  <li>To influence the  management and deployment of resources against the current challenges and  trends. </li>\r\n  <li>Provides management  information on crime situation. </li>\r\n  <li>Deals with complaints  against the police </li>\r\n  <li>Keeps and maintains a  register of all registered Arms Dealers </li>\r\n  <li>Provides secretarial  for the National Focal Point Committee meetings and Arms Quota Board Raffle. </li>\r\n  <li>Compiles and supply crime  statistics to the Police</li>\r\n</ul><br/>\r\n<h3>Communication Unit</h3>\r\n<p>The Unit is responsible for Monitoring and controlling radio  communication within the Botswana Police Service. It also receives reports from  members of the public and dispatch them to relevant Police establishment for  action. It<strong> is formed by the following Sections;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>National  Control Room</strong>&nbsp;</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Crime Input  Bureau (CIB)</strong> </li>\r\n  </ul><br/>\r\n<h3>Stock Theft Unit</h3>\r\n<p>The unit deals with all issues relating to  stock theft and its responsibilities are:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Provides management  and administration of the Stock Theft activities by ensuring that Police  operatives are advised on the strategies to employ, and how to deploy the  resources to control the crime.</li>\r\n  <li>Ensures that police  response is appropriate and achieve the desired outcome. </li>\r\n  <li>Be liaison office  between Stock Theft unit and other BPS formations as well as other Government  Departments/Ministries </li>\r\n  <li>Promotes effective  communication throughout the unit in order to ensure the maximum contribution  of individual and teams in meeting the corporate goals and objectives of the  Police service</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',	'Operations HQ',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=190',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:36:54',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(191,	'Criminal Investigations Department',	' <ul>\r\n    <li>The Criminal Investigation Department (CID) is a Branch  in the Botswana Police Service which is headed by a Director. </li>\r\n    <li>The Branch prevents and detects crime and is responsible  for the investigation of serious crimes. </li>\r\n    <li>CID consists of specialised units such as Serious  Crime Squad, Diamond and Narcotics Squad, Crime Prevention Unit, National  Central Bureau (NCB) Interpol. The Branch has establishment at Stations,  Districts and Divisions.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<h3>Serious Crime Squad </h3>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The Unit is headed by an Officer Commanding holding  the rank of Senior Superintendent</li>\r\n    <li>It is responsible for motor vehicle theft, motor  vehicle clearance and fraud related investigations. Motor vehicle clearance services  are currently done at the Serious Crime Squad (Gaborone)  Lobatse, Ghanzi, Maun, Francistown,  Selibe-Phikwe, Serowe, Mahalapye, Tsabong and Kasane. The offices issue Southern  African Regional Police Chiefs Cooperation Organization (SARPCCO) clearances  for vehicle movement within the SADC region if the vehicle originates from one  member country to another. This arrangement helps both the customers and the  individual Police Services from issuing duplicitous documentation for the  movement of the same vehicle across transitory countries.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<h3>Diamond and Narcotics Squad</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The Unit curbs crime related to diamonds, and the  illicit use or dealing in any type of narcotics. </li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p></p>\r\n<h3>Crime Prevention Unit</h3>\r\n<p>The Unit  educates the public on crime prevention issues and coordinates initiatives such  as Neighbourhood Watch Schemes and Cluster committees It provides tips on how to  secure property and on personal safety</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<h3>Interpol National Bureau</h3>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>As a member of the International Police Organisation, the  unit links Botswana Police Service with 185 other Police organizations around  the globe through a closed and secure communication system called i24/7. </li>\r\n    <li>Any information sought from any member country can be  availed immediately throughout the system. </li>\r\n    <li>Other Law Enforcement Departments like Immigration,  Customs, DCEC etc benefit immensely from the i24/7 facility.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p></p>\r\n<h3>Divisional CID</h3>\r\n<p>The  CID Branch works hand in hand with General Duty Branch. The Divisional CID  Officers oversees Districts CID Units under their jurisdiction and the  Districts oversee the Station CID units.</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<h3>Contact Details</h3>\r\n<p>Director of  Criminal Investigation Department<br />\r\nPhone: 3914706</p>\r\n<p>Fax: 3952651<br />\r\n  Box 1082, Gaborone </p>\r\n<p>Enquiries:  3642300</p>',	'Criminal Investigations Department',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=191',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:37:27',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(192,	'Traffic Branch',	'<p>The Traffic Branch is responsible for ensuring the safety of all those who use the roads.  The mandate is  to make the  roads safer by reducing fatal, serious, minor injuries and the protection of property damage caused by motor vehicle crashes, by:</p>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Assisting all road  users in need and to reassure those in difficulties </li>\r\n    <li>Educating members of  the public on road safety </li>\r\n    <li>Facilitating the free  flow of traffic </li>\r\n    <li>Enforcing the Road  Traffic Act/Regulations and all other laws </li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',	'Traffic Branch',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=192',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:39:30',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(193,	'Crime Intelligence Branch',	'<p>Crime Intelligence Branch (CRIB) is a Branch  of the Botswana Police Service that is at the forefront of the fight against  serious and organised crime in Botswana.  It provides a number of services to operational law enforcement to enhance the  development of criminal intelligence on serious criminality. The Branch has  offices/units at the district level and strategic and specialist units based at  the headquarters.</p>\r\n<p>As a national centre of expertise on serious and organised crime, CRIB also  conducts research and analysis on a range of specialist areas, producing  strategic intelligence.</p>\r\n<p>The following are the functions of the  Branch:</p>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Gather information  from all sources and to analyse that information to provide <strong>tactical</strong> and <strong>strategic intelligence</strong> on the  existence, identities and capabilities of criminal suspects and enterprises to  further crime prevention and enforcement objectives of the Botswana Police  Service. </li>\r\n    <li>Gather, correlate,  evaluate and analyse information. </li>\r\n    <li>Identify any  potential or existing threat to the security of the country or its people. </li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;Effectively  monitor the activities of persons, and organisations suspected of engaging in  an organised criminal enterprise, and of persons and organizations suspected of  conducting or planning violent acts against the citizens of the country. </li>\r\n    <li>Study crime  incidents, identify and analyse crime patterns, crime trends and crime problems  for the development of tactics, policies and strategies to address the problem. </li>\r\n    <li>To uproot police  corruption. </li>\r\n  </ul>',	'Crime Intelligence Branch',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=193',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:40:47',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(194,	'Forensic Science Services',	'<p>Forensic Science Services Branch was established in 2006. Its functions are;</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Provides forensic  services and management of criminal records towards the fight against crime. </li>\r\n    <li>Oversight of the  technical output of crime scene investigators at police stations throughout the  country. </li>\r\n    <li>Provides training in  forensic science for pre- and in-service training programs at the Police College </li>\r\n    <li>Provides expert  testimony </li>\r\n    <li>Provides  investigative leads/intelligence </li>\r\n  </ul><br/>\r\n<p>The Units are;</p>\r\n\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>Criminal Records  Bureau </li>\r\n    <li>Forensic Science  Laboratory </li>\r\n    <li>Forensic Pathology </li>\r\n    <li>Crime Scene  Investigators (evidence collectors) at the Police &nbsp;stations </li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',	'Forensic Science Services',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=194',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:43:24',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(195,	'Northern Division',	'<p>This is the oldest division as available information shows that by as  far as 1964 before independence the division was in existence together with  Southern division.&nbsp; It has been in  existence during the colonial era.&nbsp; The division by far is the largest in terms  of policing area.&nbsp; It has six (6) districts namely 1, 5, 7, 8, 10 and 15  comprising of thirty two (32) Police Stations.&nbsp; It shares a long border  with Zimbabwe on the north  eastern side and north western side, Namibia  on the North West side, South Africa  on the eastern side while only 500 m is shared with Zambia on the north.&nbsp; The  division covers twenty (20) Parliamentary Constituencies and according to the  2001 population census statistics there were 600&nbsp;074 people in this area.  However, the number might have doubled owing to the political situation in the  area due to influx of illegal immigrants from neighboring countries, and other  geographical factors which caused the upsurge in population.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 1 District</h3>\r\n<p>The district is one of the busiest in the division,  as all of its Police Stations are mostly in and around the city which is its  main catch point.&nbsp; It has five (5) Police Stations being Kutlwano, Tonota,  Tatitown, Gerald and Matsiloje.&nbsp; Of all its stations Tatitown is the only  one that covers a large area going as far as Mokubilo village about 120  kilometers from Francistown.&nbsp;  Matsiloje covers most area around Botswana/Zimbabwe border.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 5 District</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>This district is the biggest of them all.&nbsp; It covers areas from  Gweta to Seronga/Shakawe.&nbsp; The district shares a border with Namibia on the north west side and its stations are Maun,  Seronga, Sehitwa, Gumare and Shakwe with Maun as the busiest due to the fact  that the village itself is a tourism destination and growing at an alarming  rate which attracts a lot of people, both job seekers and potential  investors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>No. 7 District</h3>\r\n<p>This district is the smallest in the division comprising of five (5)  Police Stations.&nbsp; Stations include Kasane, Kasane Airport,  Pandamatenga, Kazungula, and Kavimba.&nbsp; It shares its border with Zimbabwe on the north western side and it is  located in the Chobe District which is Botswana\'s biggest tourism  destination.&nbsp; It also shares about 500 m border with Zambia along Chobe  River and Namibia on the north western  side.&nbsp; Despite the influx of tourist in the area, it has a small  population owing to the fact that it is mostly reserved for wildlife.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 8 District</h3>\r\n<p>The district is fast growing as it sees more developments taking place  in areas like Letlhakane and Orapa where there are mine explorations taking  place.&nbsp; It has six (6) Police stations and of all the six stations, four  are policing mining areas.&nbsp; Letlhakane and Orapa are policing the Debswana  mines of DK9-11 and Damtshaa, and the villages around them.&nbsp; There are a lot  of developments taking place around this areas making it one of the busiest  Policing areas.&nbsp; Dukwi and Sowa also police the Sua pan mines and Mowana  mines.&nbsp; Rakops polices areas like CKGR, Xere and other villages.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 10 District</h3>\r\n<p>This is the second biggest district in the  division.&nbsp; It lies on the eastern side of Botswana  and shares borders with South Africa  along Mashatu area at Bainesdrift and Zanzibar  areas which is a tourist destination.&nbsp; Its stations are Selibe Phikwe and  Botshabelo which are in the Selibe Phikwe town area and policing the town and  its surrounding villages.&nbsp; Serule, Bainesdrift, Semolale and Bobonong  Police stations forms part of the district\'s stations.&nbsp; Bainsdrift,  Semolale and Bobonong are based along Botswana/Zimbabwe and Botswana/South  Africa borders.&nbsp; The district shares its policing borders with No. 2  District at Mogapi village.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 15 District</h3>\r\n<p>This district was established and was formed  by splitting some stations that used to form part of No. 1 District.&nbsp; It  polices the other part of the City of Francistown  and other surrounding villages.&nbsp; Its stations include Francistown which covers areas from Donga to  Monarch location up to Dumela Industrial and surrounding farms.&nbsp; <strong>Tutume,  Masunga and Tshesebe</strong> also form part of the district.&nbsp; The  district shares the border with Zimbabwe  on the north eastern side and north western part.&nbsp; It is mostly affected  by the influx of illegal immigrants.&nbsp; Since Francistown is the second city of the country  it serves the northern part of the country with Government services hence it  has large catchments in population.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>',	'Northern Division',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=195',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:46:14',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(196,	'South Central Division',	'<p>South Central Division was established in 1997 after the proposal to reorganize the Divisions, of which by then were only two which were North and South Divisions. South Central Division comprises of four (4) Districts, namely No. 2,3,12 and 13. There are 21 Police stations headquartered in Broadhurst in Gaborone.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 2 District</h3>\r\n<p>This District covers the largest policing area more than other Districts. It has seven (7) Police stations, Serowe, Palapye, Mahalapye, Machaneng, Maunatlala, Shoshong and Martinsdrift Police stations. Serowe covers the largest area which extends to Dimajwe and Malatswai while others cover small areas for instance, Mahalapye is surrounded by Palapye in the north, Shoshong in the west, Machaneng in the east and Serowe in the North West.</p> \r\n<h3>No. 3 District</h3>\r\n<p>The District is one of the busiest in the division in terms of general crime. It has five (5) police stations, namely Broadhurst, Central , Urban , Tlokweng and Borakanelo Police Stations. Broadhurst polices areas of Phakalane Police Post up to Oodi/Modipane villages while CPS covers the central part of the City (Main Mall, Government Enclave, Village and University of Botswana areas.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 12 District</h3>\r\n<p>The district covers area mostly in the Kgatleng District Council. It has four(4) Police Stations namely Mochudi, Sikwane, Olifandrift and Dibete Police Stations. Oliphantsdrift and Sikwane Police Stations cover  the area along the Botswana/South African border where cases of stock theft are rampant. Dibete covers an area along A.1 road from Artesia to Mookane turnoff and other neighboring villages (Mookane, Mmaphashalala).</p>\r\n<h3>No. 13 District</h3>\r\n<p>The District is also one of the busiest in the division in terms of general crime. It covers Gaborone West, Mogoditshane, Naledi, Sir Seretse Khama Airport (SSKA) and Ramotswa Police Stations. Mogoditshane, Gaborone West and Naledi are busiest in the district. Mogoditshane covers areas of Tsolamosese, Nkoyaphiri, Gabane, Kopong, Metsimotlhabe, Diphiring Lands and Mogoditshane village which is an industrial hub where there are many foreign vehicle importer garages. Gaborone West covering Phase I, II and IV, Block 5, 6 and 9 and Kgale View up to Pula Spar. Naledi covers areas of Mokolodi, Notwane farms, Game City and Naledi location which is also highly inhabited. SSKA covers Mmopane village, Block 7 and 8, Gaborone North farms and SSK Airport where some officers are deployed on daily basis.</p>',	'South Central Division',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=196',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:54:23',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(197,	'Southern Division',	'<p>Southern  Division is situated in the southern part of Botswana with its headquarters  located in Lobatse. The Division is composed of five(5) Police Districts namely  No\'s 4,6,9,11 and 14. There are 25 police stations within this division. The  Division polices an area of over 4000 km2 with a population of almost  381&nbsp;595 according to the 1991 population census. It also polices the  Diamond mine at Jwaneng, High Court, Botswana Meat Commission and other government  structures, including the Trans-Kalahari    Highway which is a major route to South Africa and Namibia. Among others this Division  polices four Game Reserves/National Parks namely; Central Kalahari Game  Reserve, Kutse, Mabuasehube and Trans-Frontier. The following constituencies  are found within this Division; Gantsi North, Gantsi South, Kgalagadi North,  Kgalagadi South, Kweneng West, Ngwaketse West, Ngwaketse South, Kanye,  Letlhakeng East, Letlhakeng West, Molepolole North, Molepolole South, Lobatse,  Borolong, Moshupa and part of South East. </p>\r\n<h3>No. 4 District </h3>\r\n<p>There  are four(4) Police Stations namely Lobatse, Woodhall, Goodhope and Ramatlabama  covering Lobatse and surrounding areas  of Ramatlabama and Goodhope.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 6 District</h3>\r\n<p>There  are four(4) Police Stations namely Gantsi, Charleshill, Kalkfontein and  Ncojane. The district is in the western part of the country sharing boarder  mostly with Namibia.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 9 District</h3>\r\n<p>The  district has six(6) Police Stations namely Tsabong, Tshane, Werda, Bokspits,  Kang and Middlepits. The District covers Kgalagadi administrative district and  shares the border with the Republic   of South Africa. It  covers the Trans Frontier  Park which is a tourist destination  for Botswana and South Africa.</p>\r\n<h3>No. 11 District</h3>\r\n<p>The  District covers five(5) Police Stations namely Molepolole, Letlhakeng,  Takatokwane, Thamaga and Sojwe. The district covers Kweneng Administrative  district. </p>\r\n<h3>No. 14 District</h3>\r\n<p>The  district is comprising of Kanye, Sejelo, Moshupa, Jwaneng, Phitshane Molopo and  Mabutsane Police Stations.  The division  covers most of the southern part of the country.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',	'Southern Division',	'mcms',	'189',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'Active',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=197',	NULL,	NULL,	'14:59:31',	0,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
(198,	'Fines and Payments',	'<h3>Fines process</h3>\r\n<p>The  procedure covering the payment of Admission of Guilt is set out in the Criminal  Procedure and evidence Act (Cap. 08:02 of Botswana Laws)<br />\r\n<a href=\"#\"><strong>Link to the law</strong></a></p>\r\n<p>When  any person is charged with a traffic offence which it is believed a court on  conviction would not impose a sentence of imprisonment or a fine not exceeding  P1 000.00, and accused person admits his guilt, such person may be permitted to  pay admission of guilt fine at the Police Station.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The  procedure is outlined below:-</strong></p>\r\n<p>Charged  motorists are issued with Form BP125 (MOTOR VEHICLE AND ROAD TRAFFIC OFFENCES)  - detailing the particulars of the accused, names and service number of Police officer  laying the charge and his signature, date and time of offence, jurisdiction,  registration number of motor vehicle driven by the accused, offence or offences  committed, amount to be paid, signature of the accused and signed date, date  and time to appear at the Police Station if accused declines to pay a traffic  fine</p>\r\n<p>Once  the accused protest the charge, a summons accompanied by a charge sheet &nbsp;are issued to him/her for court appearance.  Court procedure is discussed in detail under the Criminal Procedure and  Evidence Act (Cap 08:02 of Botswana Laws)</p>\r\n<p><strong>If  the accused pays the procedure is as hereunder:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Form  BP125 is in triplicate, the original (which is white) is issued to the accused,  duplicate (which is green) is filed in the docket and the triplicate (which is  pink) remains in the book)</p>\r\n<p>After  payment of fine, the accused is issued with Form Rev22 &ndash; this is a receipt detailing  particulars of the accused, date of payment, names, rank and service number of  officer accepting money, amount paid, place paid, signatures of both accused  and the Police Office administering the process.</p>',	'Fines and Payments',	'mcms',	'',	'2011-02-04',	NULL,	'',	NULL,	'bps-content.php?cid=198',	NULL,	NULL,	'15:02:17',	46,	0,	NULL,	NULL),
