(412,	'Criminal Investigations Department',	'<ul>\r\n    <li>The Criminal Investigation Department (CID) is a Branch  in the Botswana Police Service which is headed by a Director.</li>\r\n    <li>The Branch prevents and detects crime and is responsible  for the investigation of serious crimes.</li>\r\n    <li>CID consists of specialised units such as Serious  Crime Squad, Diamond and Narcotics Squad, Crime Prevention Unit, National  Central Bureau (NCB) Interpol. The Branch has establishment at Stations,  Districts and Divisions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Serious Crime Squad</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>The Unit is headed by an Officer Commanding holding  the rank of Senior Superintendent</li>\r\n    <li>It is responsible for motor vehicle theft, motor  vehicle clearance and fraud related investigations. Motor vehicle clearance services  are currently done at the Serious Crime Squad (Gaborone)  Lobatse, Ghanzi, Maun, Francistown,  Selibe-Phikwe, Serowe, Mahalapye, Tsabong and Kasane. The offices issue Southern  African Regional Police Chiefs Cooperation Organization (SARPCCO) clearances  for vehicle movement within the SADC region if the vehicle originates from one  member country to another. This arrangement helps both the customers and the  individual Police Services from issuing duplicitous documentation for the  movement of the same vehicle across transitory countries.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Diamond and Narcotics Squad</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>The Unit curbs crime related to diamonds, and the  illicit use or dealing in any type of narcotics.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Crime Prevention Unit</h3>\r\n<p>The Unit  educates the public on crime prevention issues and coordinates initiatives such  as Neighbourhood Watch Schemes and Cluster committees It provides tips on how to  secure property and on personal safety</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Interpol National Bureau</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>As a member of the International Police Organisation, the  unit links Botswana Police Service with 185 other Police organizations around  the globe through a closed and secure communication system called i24/7.</li>\r\n    <li>Any information sought from any member country can be  availed immediately throughout the system.</li>\r\n    <li>Other Law Enforcement Departments like Immigration,  Customs, DCEC etc benefit immensely from the i24/7 facility.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Divisional CID</h3>\r\n<p>The  CID Branch works hand in hand with General Duty Branch. The Divisional CID  Officers oversees Districts CID Units under their jurisdiction and the  Districts oversee the Station CID units.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Contact Details</h3>\r\n<p>Director of  Criminal Investigation Department<br />\r\nPhone: 3914706</p>\r\n<p>Fax: 3952651<br />\r\nBox 1082, Gaborone</p>\r\n<p>Enquiries:  3642300</p>',	'Criminal Investigations Department',	'mcms',	'235',	'2011-03-14',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=412',	NULL,	'',	'10:39:41',	237,	0,	'',	''),
(379,	'History of BPS',	'<h3>HISTORY</h3>\r\n<p>The history of policing in this country dates back to the colonial era with the establishment of the Bechuanaland Mounted Police in 1885 headed by Lieutenant Colonel Frederick Carrington, with a strength of 500 men. A year later the name changed to Bechuanaland Border Police and then to Bechuanaland Protectorate Police in 1902. In 1966 Bechuanaland Protectorate Police became Botswana Police Force after the country attained independence from the British rule.</p>\r\n<p>Some natives of the Protectorate perceived the police institution as foreign, particularly that most police officers were migrants from Basutoland (current Lesotho) and Southern Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe). Qualifications for enlisting was more inclined to physique and height as opposed to academic qualifications, thus portraying police officers as confrontational, scary and always all out to pounce on the unsuspecting public.</p>\r\n<p>These perceptions, apparently contributed to creating a drift between the police and the public they were supposed to serve. It should however, be noted that even where there is mutual understanding between the police and the public, some people still view each other with suspicion. This retrogressive behaviour has inadvertently contributed to the various causes of the ascension of crime and benefited the criminal fraternity.</p>\r\n<p>This state of affairs remained so for years until a deliberate move was taken to localise policing by enlisting Batswana in the Police Force.  The legacy from the past was carried on albeit an improved state owing to the fact that the locals were only brought in as messengers and getting a rank beyond trooper was an envy to the handful of Batswana cadres. With the dawn of   independence came some transformation that entailed the fast tracking of a localisation programme. However, the police leadership remained in the hands of the whites until 1971 when Mr Simon Hirschfeld was appointed the first Motswana Police Commissioner. He retired in 1995 after serving as Police Commissioner for 24 consecutive years.</p>\r\n<p>Three other Batswana have since served as Commissioners, and they are Messrs Norman Seduma Moleboge (1995 -2004), and Edwin Jenamiso Batshu (2004 - 2007).  The incumbent Thebeyame Edward Tsimako succeeded the former in June 2007.</p>\r\n<p>In 1971 the first batch of eight (8) women, comprising Ms Cynthia Keakantswe, Sylvia Muzila, Ednah Gilika, Kgomotso Mosimanyana, Didimalang Koronomio, Vivian Mhaladi, Audry Busang and Annah Matshego was recruited into the Police. Since then, women numbers have been increasing with each police recruitment.</p>\r\n<p>The Commissioner of Police is appointed by the President of the Republic of Botswana as the Commander-in-Chief of the Armed Forces in terms of Section 112  (2) (e) of the Constitution of Botswana.  He is accountable to the Minister of Defence, Justice and Security and currently he is deputised by two Deputy Commissioners responsible for Operations and the other for Support Services.  The Police Service is also made up of 12 branches; General Duties, Special Support Group, Criminal Investigations Department, Departmental Management Services, Transport and Telecommunications, Botswana Police College, Traffic, Forensic Science Services, Air Support, Finance, Planning and Development, Crime Intelligence Branch, and Performance Management Systems.</p>\r\n<p>In addition to branches there are three Divisions; North, South Central and South, led by Divisional Commanders.  Within Divisions are 15 Districts, which are commanded by Officer Commanders, and 79 Police Stations led by Station Commanders. The strength of 500 men in 1885 has increased to over 10 000 with the merger of the Botswana Local Police Force and the Botswana Police Service in 2009. Apart from the regular police officers, there are Special Constables, who were introduced in 2004 to enhance police visibility.  Late in 2009, BPS introduced Police Volunteers to further augment police patrols.</p>',	'History of BPS',	'mcms',	'1',	'2011-03-14',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=379',	NULL,	'',	'08:44:59',	0,	0,	'',	''),
(467,	'Victims and Witness Support',	'<ul class=\\\"list\\\">\r\n    <li>Victims &ndash; There are supported by  offering them counselling and protection where there is clear evidence that  he/she is under threat.</li>\r\n    <li>Witnesses - There are supported  by offering them protection where there is clear evidence that he/she is under  threat. Moreover, in cases where they have to travel long distance and in cases  where they will need food, they are provided with transport, accommodation and  food.</li>\r\n</ul>',	'Victims and Witness Support',	'mcms',	'2',	'2011-04-14',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=467',	NULL,	'',	'08:48:51',	0,	0,	'',	''),
(393,	'Forensic Science Services',	'<ul>\r\n<li>Issue clearance certificates (see e-government portal)</li>\r\n<li>Analyses and identifies questioned documents</li>\r\n<li>Provides scientific investigation.</li>\r\n<li>DNA analysis for murder, rape and other sexual assault cases for linkage of the suspect to the crime.</li>	\r\n<li>DNA analysis for cases of human identification to prove/confirm relationship.</li>\r\n<li>Species Identification, fibre analysis etc</li>\r\n<li>Dagga analysis and other habit forming drugs.</li>\r\n<li>Analysis of samples of suspected poisoning cases.</li>\r\n<li>Determination of alcohol levels in cases of drunken driving and Road Traffic Act.</li>\r\n<li>Analysis of ignitable flammable liquids, paint, soil and unknown substances.</li>\r\n<li>Analysis of currency to establish authenticity.</li>\r\n<li>Determination of origin and cause of fire</li>\r\n<li>Firearms registration, serial number restoration</li>\r\n<li>Footwear and tyre marks examination and identification</li>\r\n<li>Analysis of tool marks</li>\r\n<li>Determination of cause of death</li>\r\n<li>Estimates age, gender etc in cases of death</li></ul>',	'Forensic Science Services',	'mcms',	'5',	'2011-03-14',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=393',	NULL,	'',	'09:27:23',	0,	0,	'',	''),
