(545,	'Fines And Payments',	'<h3>\r\n	Fines process</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	The procedure covering the payment of Admission of Guilt is set out in the Criminal Procedure and evidence Act (Cap. 08:02 of Botswana Laws)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<a herf=\\\"#\\\">Link to the law</a></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	When any person is charged with an offence which it is believed a court on conviction would not impose a sentence of imprisonment or a fine not exceeding P1 000.00, and accused person admits his guilt, such person may be permitted to pay admission of guilt fine at the Police Station.</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	For Traffic fines the procedure is outlined below:-</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	Charged motorists are issued with Form BP125 (MOTOR VEHICLE AND ROAD TRAFFIC OFFENCES) - detailing the particulars of the accused, names and service number of Police officer laying the charge and his signature, date and time of offence, jurisdiction, registration number of motor vehicle driven by the accused, offence or offences committed, amount to be paid, signature of the accused and signed date, date and time to appear at the Police Station if accused declines to pay a traffic fine</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Once the accused protest the charge, a summons accompanied by a charge sheet are issued to him/her for court appearance. Court procedure is discussed in detail under the Criminal Procedure and Evidence Act (Cap 08:02 of Botswana Laws)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	If the accused pays the procedure is as hereunder:</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	Form BP125 is in triplicate, the original (which is white) is issued to the accused, duplicate (which is green) is filed in the docket and the triplicate (which is pink) remains in the book)</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	After payment of fine, the accused is issued with Form Rev22 - this is a receipt detailing particulars of the accused, date of payment, names, rank and service number of officer accepting money, amount paid, place paid, signatures of both accused and the Police Office administering the process.</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	As the BPS we are committed to ensuring that our communities remain safe and secure</h3>\r\n',	'Fine-and-payments',	'mcms',	'544',	'2017-11-13',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=545',	NULL,	'',	'19:03:58',	0,	NULL,	'',	''),
(569,	'Guidelines for Cyclists',	'<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Always wear helmets when riding a motor cycle or bicycle</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		When riding a motorcycle always carry your driver&#39;s licence</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Never Drink and ride</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Adhere to traffic signals, markings and signs</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Avoid using cell phone when riding.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Do not ride at high speeds. You may lose control and your life in the process</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Do not ride your motor cycle on to the footpath</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Use your head lights when riding a motor cycle</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Understand the signals given by other road users and use the same when riding</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Never stop abruptly in traffic. Pull over and slow down</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		When passing a stationery vehicle allow sufficient clearance for the motor vehicle doors which may open suddenly</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Do not try and weave your way through stationery or slow moving motor vehicles</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Always ride with both hands on the handlebar except when signaling</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Don&#39;t sit children on fuel tanks or stand them in front of the rider in motor cycle</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',	'Guidelines for Cyclists',	'mcms',	'9',	'2017-11-13',	'',	'',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=569',	NULL,	'',	'20:04:51',	403,	NULL,	'',	''),
(547,	'Habit Forming Drugs',	'<h3>\r\n	The most common drugs in Botswana are:</h3>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Dagga remains the most abused illicit or illegal drug in Botswana due to its easy availability.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Cocaine is the second placed abused drug with rock or crack cocaine being the most abused drug.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Ecstasy</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Alcohol</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>\r\n	Legal implications of drugs abuse</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	A person who is convicted under the Drugs and Related Substances Act No. 18 of 1992 will in his/her whole lifetime have a Criminal Record which may deter him/her from being employed by any organization.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	There is also likely hood of imprisonment thereby spending time which someone could have developed himself to better his/her life as the penalties are so stiff.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A person arrested for possession of dagga weighing less than 60 grams may find himself or herself in jail for a period not exceeding 3 years and a fine of P1000.00.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A person arrested for possession of dagga weighing more than 60 grams may find himself or herself in jail for a period of not more than 5 years and to a fine of not less than P1500.00 or not more than P5000.00.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A person who deals (sells, cultivate, import, manufacture etc) dagga may find himself or herself in jail for a period of not less 5 years or not more than 10 years and to fine of not less than P7000.00. whilst to cocaine, ecstasy, mandrax and other related drugs can be jailed for a period not less than 10 years or more than 15 years and to a fine of not less than P15000.00.</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	Social implications</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Social implications of drug abuse in both &quot;children and adults&quot;, may result in:</strong></p>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Expulsion from work or school</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Sale of valuables from home to finance purchases of drugs</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Children drop out of school</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Road accidents</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Kidnapping of women and gang rapist.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Women and child abuse. etc:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n',	'Habit Forming Drugs',	'mcms',	'544',	'2017-11-13',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=547',	NULL,	'',	'19:08:58',	0,	NULL,	'',	''),
(548,	'How to report Crime',	'<p>\r\n	Botswana Police Service is grateful to the citizens, business community, tourists/visitors and government employees for their continued support and would encourage anyone with information they feel may be relevant to Police to come forward.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	If you have been the victim of crime, have witnessed a crime or &nbsp;would simply like to tell Police that a crime has been committed &nbsp;there are several ways to do it. You can:</p>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Contact the nearest police station in person or police officer in patrol</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Dial either 999 (emergency number) or toll free number or &nbsp;Landline for that police station</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	You will be asked the following questions:</p>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Nature of the offence</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Time of offence</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Locality eg plot No, street, H/No or any nearest structure</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Identity of the suspect or physical description of the suspect</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Method of operation if known eg weapon used</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Witnesses where possible</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The reporter should also request the name of the officer received the report</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The reporter should not temper with the scene</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The reporter should take into consideration his/her own personal security and safety</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	When reporting a crime it is important to put your safety and the safety of other people first. In case you are not satisfied with the service or response, ask for any senior officer in charge.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Where possible preserve the scene of crime. Contamination of crime scene might lead to loss of valuable evidence or you might implicate yourself by leaving your fingerprints/DNA at the scene.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	PLEASE NOTE THE FOLLOWING:</p>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		In case of fire, bomb blasting, road traffic accident it is important that service providers Police, Ambulance, Fire Brigade etc have full and unhindered access to the crime scene or injured.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		When reporting remember to remain calm and exercise patience as the leading questions that are being asked at time of reporting are to establish what is expected at the scene of crime.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		You can report a crime anonymously through your telephone. Your privacy or identity will not be revealed</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	Service Branches:</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	You may locate the service branche in charge in the &nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.gov.bw/en/Ministries--Authorities/Ministries/State-President/Botswana-Police-Service-/Tools-and-Services/Ministry-Directory/?FromPageID=1590&amp;FromPageType=1&amp;pid=1&amp;ClearSearch=true&amp;Branch=-1\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Useful Links</a></p>\r\n',	'How to report Crime',	'mcms',	'544',	'2017-11-13',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=548',	NULL,	'',	'19:12:01',	0,	NULL,	'',	''),
(549,	'Sexual Offenses',	'<p>\r\n	Sexual offences of concern are rape, defilement, indecent assault and incest. These are usually committed by friends or close relatives. There are few cases where these offences are committed by unknown people. Of the above offences, rape is the most common. Perpetrators sometimes date victims to entertainment places and later rape them. Due to excessive alcohol consumption, some victims realize they have been raped when they wake up the following day. As for defilement, young girls are enticed with money or valuable items to consent to sexual acts.</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	Reporting rape</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	The incident should be immediately reported to the police. The sooner an incident is reported to the police the more forensic evidence can be collected, and this may help secure a conviction.</p>\r\n<br />\r\n<h3>\r\n	Advantages of reporting rape</h3>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		An opportunity to present your side of the story.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The attacker may be prosecuted.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Reporting a frequent attacker may stop future attacks.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The victim may receive medical assistance in time.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>\r\n	NB: Reporting an incident does not mean the attacker will be prosecuted.</h4>\r\n<h3>\r\n	Police Procedures regarding rape</h3>\r\n<p>\r\n	All police investigations start with the collection of forensic evidence. These tests are done by taking swabs from any part of your body that the assailant came in contact with. It is important that you do not do any of the following before the swabs are taken:</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Do not wash<br />\r\n	Do not change your clothes</p>\r\n',	'Sexual Offenses',	'mcms',	'544',	'2017-11-13',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=549',	NULL,	'',	'19:12:51',	0,	NULL,	'',	''),
(550,	'Stock Theft',	'<p>\r\n	Stealing of stock usually is committed by herd boys or syndicates, incidents of stock are more common in areas that are close to urban centres where there are lucrative markets for beef. Criminals, who operate in syndicates, re-brand stolen cattle to defraud original owners.</p>\r\n<h3>\r\n	A lot of livestock is stolen due to the following reasons:</h3>\r\n<ul class=\\\"listing\\\">\r\n	<li>\r\n		Livestock left astray.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Livestock left unbranded and not earmarked</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		The responsibility is left solely with herd boys</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		Late or failure to pay herd boys accordingly</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	Farmers are encouraged to form up into clusters so as to intensify the fight against stock theft. Moreover, they are encouraged to take a leading role in security of their livestock.</p>\r\n<h4>\r\n	NB: The public is urged to report to the police people they suspect to be operating livestock criminal syndicates and ascertain the authenticity of any livestock before purchasing them.</h4>\r\n',	'Stock Theft',	'mcms',	'544',	'2017-11-13',	'',	'Active',	'',	'bps-content.php?cid=550',	NULL,	'',	'19:13:39',	0,	NULL,	'',	''),
